column7: I think I have figured this out. Transport went to production around June This switched the valuation class of period work schedule ndx from to This setting will generate shift premium. In late January transport went to production which flipped the valuation class back to Because this change is not effective dated to a reasonable date, any time anyone who is on shifts CH ND or FM ND is retro ed back to then the shift premiums will be recalculated at and the money recovered. I am attaching a list of employees who are all on the above mentioned shifts. I would like to suggest that someone contact these people and give them the option of either having a forced retro done to recoup the money or set infotype so that retro will not occur and put them on a repayment plan for money paid during the period they were incorrectly paid. I copied another ee back to QAS ee and ran a simulation on time evaluation and it is indeed clawing back. A lot of these people have not had retro happen in a while, but once it does happen, you will have the same situation as ee If you have any questions, let me know. Sheila I'm copying you on an email where Harry wants to look into this. I ran a logged changes report and saw that on somebody probably the time manager went in and viewed some absences from as early as didn't make any changes, then saved the absences again. This caused a retro during the next payroll run. I know Sashi had worked on several issues relating to shift premiums, but I don't know what was fixed and what wasn't. There appear to be changes to the shift premiums that went back in history, that caused this problem the problem is, if other employees are in the same situation, they will also have their pay taken back retroactively! By the way, I have already copied this employee to HQ so that he she can be reviewed in the quality system instead of production.

column6: Any combination of shipments or deliveries can be combined onto the same load as long as they are referencing the same carrier number. Pick list numbers and could have been, and probably should have been, combined onto one shipment as they had the same shipment specification number, which meant that all infomration in the VASPEZ table was the same between the two pick lists. However, pick list number should not have been able to be combine, and it wasn't. VSS did allow it to go on the same load since all pick lists were referencing the same carrier We have completed shipments for Ford both for Production and Service Parts. We need to bill our orders but all Ford shipment have been grouped together under Load in the MIPS system. The shipments must be separated because they have different customer numbers Carla Blackwell x
column7: Any combination of shipments or deliveries can be combined onto the same load as long as they are referencing the same carrier number. Pick list numbers and could have been, and probably should have been, combined onto one shipment as they had the same shipment specification number, which meant that all infomration in the VASPEZ table was the same between the two pick lists. However, pick list number should not have been able to be combine, and it wasn't. VSS did allow it to go on the same load since all pick lists were referencing the same carrier the question is why shouldn't we. I checked the shipments and there is no reason to deny putting them in one load. A load is principally just a carrier. You put the packages on a carrier but you don't know how far it drives. For example If you make a load for three customers, the carrier can drive to a HUB and the divide it in three different carriers. Therefore it is allowed to put them together. Greeting Stefan EDT How could VSS allow these packages shipments to be combined. John > Not sure if this was an IAS or VSS issue.

column6: Sent Thursday, October Collins, Larry Colston, Mark Blankenship, Darin Adams, Scott RE Honda DTR NDT ASN incorrect on quick receive label I was able to discern the root cause. Pick list number was issued for shipment number Pick list number was issued for shipment number Both shipments were worked up independently of one another, which is why they both had a quick receive. The ship center then combined the shipments, but forgot to verify that the quick receive labels matched the shipment number and if print if not. Anytime shipments are combined, master labels and quick receive labels should be verified, and reprinted if needed. Attached are pick list numbers and The predefined shipment numbers that VSS assigned to each pick list is in the top middle of the pick list. John Robert Clawson, Business Analyst Process and Information North America Shipment number consisted of two pick list numbers I believe the issue was that the pick lists were worked up separately, which would allow for the printing of the quick receive label. The shipment numbers were different, one referred to shipment number and the other referred to shipment number These shipments were combined with shipment number being the main shipment. This would cause an issue with only one of the quick receive labels. In order to confirm I need to reprint pick list numbers and to determine what shipment number that were given to begin with.
